<font color="#FF0000">A HAUNTING MEMORY </font><br>
<tt>Wed Apr 23  1:12:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The guy that haunts my memory was a 1st LT I met at the Cam Ranh Bay O-Club on my way out to R&amp;R.  It was 2 in the afternoon, I had nothing better to do, and the place had 21 air conditioners, all working.  He was the only other guy in the place; so I went over and introduced myself.  He was on courier duty, and had just flew in from the US.  He had been wounded twice, rather badly the second time, and his platoon had been shot up quite a bit along with him.<br><br>
He seemed to be normal enough until the Vietnamese waitress came over to take our order. His face got a look that would freeze a blast furnace, but he was civil enough when he ordered. As soon as the waitress was out of earshot; he proceeded to tell me that if he got his way he would start at the southern tip of the delta and go all the way to the Chinese border and pave every square inch of Vietnam over with cement. I have absolutely no doubt he meant every word.<br><br>
Physically there were no signs of any wounds, and he looked handsome and healthy. Psychologically, he's one of the scariest persons I've ever met in my life. Every so often I remember that scene with a man whose name I can't recall; wonder what became of him; and do the only thing I can do - pray for him.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


